  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Linked List Cycle\n\nReturn whether a linked list eventually loops back to an earlier node instead of ending at `None`.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: head = [10,20,30,40], tail connects to index 1\nOutput: true\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: head = [5,6,7], tail connects to no node\nOutput: false\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: head = [1], tail connects to index 0\nOutput: true\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- The judge provides a `ListNode` class with `val` and `next` fields.\n- Node values fit in normal signed integer range.\n- The total number of nodes across one test case is kept small enough for local execution.\n\n## Follow-up\n\nSolve it using constant extra memory.",
  "editorial": "Move one pointer by one step and another by two steps. A cycle exists exactly when the two pointers meet.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def hasCycle(self, head):\n        slow = fast = head\n        while fast and fast.next:\n            slow = slow.next\n            fast = fast.next.next\n            if slow is fast:\n                return True\n        return False\n```",
  "hints": [
    "A faster pointer can only meet a slower pointer when a loop exists.",
    "If the fast pointer reaches the end, the list is acyclic."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def hasCycle(self, head):\n        pass\n"
  },
  "entrypoint": {
    "class_name": "Solution",
    "method_name": "hasCycle"
  },
  "checker": {
    "type": "exact"
  },
  "time_limit_ms": 2000,
  "memory_limit_mb": 256,
